                            strong.mr10 B.
                            | There are now 410 workers at #[u FaSinPat] ('Fabrica sin Patrones' or 'Factory without Bosses'), having hired over 170 new workers in four years of autonomous control. The factory is #[strong widely known] as Zanon, the name under the previous owner, Luis Zanon, who #[strong accumulated] some US$170 million in #[strong debt], and #[strong shut down] the factory, #[strong firing] the workers.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 C.
                            | Argentinian government and businesses were in chaos at the time, with the government dissolving repeatedly and defaulting on $88 billion of debt, inflation #[strong skyrocketing] and people demanding money from banks who had closed their doors.
                    div(class="paperNews-block")
                        p
                            strong.mr10 D.
                            |  Like over 200 Argentinian workplaces facing similar conditions, the workers chose spontaneously to run the factory themselves, and continued maintenance and production, to keep trading on their own behalf.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 E.
                            |  Now thirty workers have travelled the 1,200 kilometers to Buenos Aires, presenting a #[strong petition] containing thousands of signatures from all over the world at the central courthouse, and mobilizing outside.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 F.
                            |  "With these actions we are marking a playing ground for the judge," said Raul Godoy, Zanon worker and General Secretary of the Ceramists' Union.
                div(class="paperNews" layout="grid" paperNews="2")
                    div(class="paperNews-block")
                        p
                            strong.mr10 G.
                            | As the government has continued its legal #[strong assault] upon the Zanon factory, at least one factory employee has been reported to have suffered repeated threats and violence at the hand of unknown attackers.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 H.
                            | Esteban Magnani, author of El Cambio Silencioso (The Silent Change), a book about worker cooperatives in Argentina told  #[i UpsideDownWorld.org], "In Neuquen you have Jorge Sobisch, a right-wing governor who wants to be the new [President] #[u Carlos Menem] ... wants to show how tough he is ... Zanon is very #[strong politicized] and famous, which is bad for a governor who wants to be seen as a right-wing savior. Sobisch feels the need to #[strong crack down] now, because the longer he waits, the more powerful Zanon becomes." Some of the workers feel that Sobisch may be approving the attacks or may be guilty in failing to defend the workers.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 I.
                            | Magnani indicates incumbent President #[u Néstor  Kirchner], described by Wikipedia as "a #[u Peronist] with #[strong leftist] leanings", might defend Zanon. "One of Kirchner’s flags is human rights. Now with this kidnapping and the continued threats, Kirchner shouldn’t have any excuse to not do something about this."
                    div(class="paperNews-block")
                        p
                            strong.mr10 J.
                            | "Subway workers, train workers, airline workers, other recuperated businesses and many other sectors have made it clear that the employees at Zanon will not be alone." Says one Zanon worker, "We are willing to defend the factory with our lives."
                        p
                            strong.mr10 K.
                            | It may not come to that. Governor Sobisch has been attempting to #[strong evict] the workers of Zanon in an #[strong ongoing], highly politicized legal battle for several years. Sobisch has been ordered by the Federal Supreme Court of Argentina to evict the workers as soon as possible.
                        p
                            strong.mr10 L.
                            | Other sources consulted about the past record of behavior by Sobisch do not reflect a record of #[strong overt] violence against the workers.  At least one source from October 2004 said that Sobish wants the workers to leave the Zanon factory and work instead in a government-sponsored micro-enterprise project for unemployed workers, constructing prefabricated houses.
                        p Read the full story here: #[a(href="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Argentinian_workers_preparing_to_defend_control_of_factory" target="_blank") https://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Argentinian_workers_preparing_to_defend_control_of_factory]
                    div(class="paperNews-block")
                        img(src="unit_1/module_1/assets/images/act_4_4.jpg" alt="" class="u-responsive-img" img-fit="cover h100 w100")
